Firstly, UV–vis absorption and fluorescence spectra were used to determine the basic fluorescence properties of CA-PEI. As mentioned above, the absorption peak at around 233 nm originates from π–π* transition caused by CO on the CA molecule, and the absorption peak at 280 nm originates from n–σ* transition caused by isolated amino groups, carboxyl groups and hydroxyl groups. The absorption band of 300–650 nm should be attributed to the n–π* transition caused by a small amount of chromophore aggregation (Fig. 3
                        a). Surprisingly, CA-PEI molecules have obvious dual excitation and dual emission phenomena. And the two optimal excitation and emission wavelengths are (Ex = 280 nm, Em = 305 nm) and (Ex = 353 nm, Em = 443 nm) (Fig. 3a), respectively. It is generally believed that the fluorescence emission at (Ex = 280 nm, Em = 305 nm) is due to n–σ* transition, and the fluorescence emission at (Ex = 353 nm, Em = 443 nm) is caused by n–π* transition. Moreover, CA-PEI molecule has two independent emission centers (Fig. 3b). When the excitation wavelength changes from 260 to 290 nm, the emission wavelength stabilizes at 305 nm. While as the excitation wavelength changes from 300 to 420 nm, the emission wavelength stabilizes at 443 nm. Interestingly, there is a small excitation peak at 280 nm in excitation spectra (Fig. 3a) which is obtained by scanning with the best emission wavelength of 443 nm. When excited with 280 nm, there is also fluorescence emission in the range of 400–500 nm (Fig. 3b). This phenomenon can be explained by the mechanism of FRET (Fig. 4
                        ). Firstly, the emission spectrum at 305 nm caused by n–σ* transition overlaps with the absorption peak derived from n–π* transition in a large area. And secondly, the isolated functional groups such as amino, hydroxyl and carboxyl groups are relatively close. Significantly, when excited with 240 nm and 250 nm, there are fluorescence emission peaks at 295 nm and 443 nm, respectively (Fig. 3b), which derive from the π–π* transition caused by CO. Due to the limitation of the instrument, it is guessed that the same phenomenon should be exhibited when using a certain range of wavelength below 240 nm for excitation. This phenomenon should also be attributed to the process of FRET. The emission spectra at 295 nm overlap with the absorption bands caused by n–σ* transition and n–π* transition at the same time, and the distance between the functional groups that produce the three transitions is close enough. In addition, the unsmooth emission peak centered at 295 nm and a slight bump at 305 nm can also prove the occurrence of FRET. The luminescence process and mechanism of CA-PEI molecules are shown in Fig. 4.
